          "text": "# Return-to-Running Plan: James\n\n## Reading Your Situation First\n\nYour physio has cleared you for 20 minutes easy only, no speed work, with walking breaks if pain appears. That's the ceiling right now, not a suggestion. Everything below is built inside that boundary.\n\nYour pre-injury pace-zone index sits at 46.5, which gives you real fitness to come back to. But the plantar fasciitis is active, and the tissue needs progressive load, not just time. The goal of this plan is to rebuild connective tissue tolerance and running continuity before any conversation about fitness or pace.\n\nOne thing worth knowing before you read further: your training paces below come from your 44:00 10K via Daniels-Gilbert zones. They represent your pre-injury fitness ceiling. Right now, easy pace (5:25 to 6:12 per km) is the only zone that applies, and you should stay at the comfortable end of that range, meaning closer to 6:12 per km, until your foot is consistently pain-free across sessions.\n\n---\n\n## Plan Overview\n\n| Parameter | Detail |\n|---|---|\n| Duration | 8 weeks |\n| Days per week | 3 |\n| Schedule | Tuesday, Thursday, Saturday |\n| Max run duration | 20 minutes per session |\n| Pace zone | Easy only (5:25 to 6:12 per km) |\n| Walk breaks | Any foot pain triggers a walk break immediately |\n| Speed work | None until physiotherapist clears it |\n| Progression | Time-based, not distance-based |\n\n---\n\n## The Core Logic\n\nPlantar fascia is a load-tolerant structure, but it responds poorly to sudden increases in tensile stress. Three things drive that stress: duration, pace, and surface hardness. You control all three. By capping sessions at 20 minutes, keeping pace easy, and progressing gradually across weeks, you give the fascia a chance to adapt rather than re-inflame.\n\nThe 10% weekly volume rule applies here in spirit, but given active injury, weeks 1 and 2 are deliberately conservative, even below what you could probably handle. That buffer is intentional. It gives you room to respond to any flare without the plan immediately breaking down.\n\nThree days per week also matters here. Connective tissue adapts more slowly than cardiovascular fitness. The off days are not wasted. They are when adaptation actually happens.\n\n---\n\n## Week-by-Week Plan\n\n### Phase 1: Re-establishing Tolerance (Weeks 1 to 3)\n\nThe priority here is consistent, pain-free running. Every session is run-walk structured. If you complete a full 20 minutes without foot pain, that is a successful session. If you need walk breaks, take them without adjusting pace when you resume.\n\n---\n\n**Week 1**\n\n*Target: 3 sessions, 12 to 15 minutes of running per session, run-walk format*\n\n| Day | Session | Structure | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy run-walk | 5 min walk warm-up, then alternate 3 min run / 2 min walk x 3 rounds | Stop if foot pain. Do not push through. |\n| Thursday | Easy run-walk | Same as Tuesday | Note any pain onset time in a log |\n| Saturday | Easy run-walk | Same as Tuesday | Soft surface preferred (grass, trail) |\n\nPace: 5:55 to 6:12 per km on the running portions.\nWeekly running time: approximately 27 minutes.\n\n---\n\n**Week 2**\n\n*Increase run intervals, same total session cap*\n\n| Day | Session | Structure | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy run-walk | 5 min walk warm-up, then alternate 4 min run / 2 min walk x 3 rounds | Watch for any new stiffness the morning after |\n| Thursday | Easy run-walk | Same as Tuesday | |\n| Saturday | Easy run-walk | Same as Tuesday | |\n\nPace: 5:55 to 6:12 per km.\nWeekly running time: approximately 36 minutes.\n\n---\n\n**Week 3**\n\n*Extend toward continuous running if Week 2 was pain-free*\n\n| Day | Session | Structure | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy run-walk | 5 min walk warm-up, then 8 min run / 2 min walk / 8 min run | Drop to walk if any foot discomfort |\n| Thursday | Easy run-walk | 5 min walk warm-up, then 10 min run / 2 min walk / 5 min run | |\n| Saturday | Easy run-walk | 5 min walk warm-up, then 12 min run / 2 min walk / 3 min run | |\n\nPace: 5:45 to 6:10 per km.\nWeekly running time: approximately 46 minutes.\n\n---\n\n### Phase 2: Building Continuity (Weeks 4 to 6)\n\nThe aim in this phase is to reach 20 continuous minutes across all three sessions. Walk breaks remain available if pain appears, but you are working toward runs that do not require them. Volume increases are modest and deliberate.\n\n---\n\n**Week 4 (Deload)**\n\nEvery third to fourth week includes a step back. This is not regression. It protects tissue adaptation and gives your foot a chance to consolidate before the next build.\n\n| Day | Session | Structure | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy run | 5 min walk warm-up, then 15 min continuous easy run | Walk break available if pain |\n| Thursday | Easy run | 5 min walk warm-up, then 12 min continuous easy run | |\n| Saturday | Easy run | 5 min walk warm-up, then 15 min continuous easy run | |\n\nPace: 5:50 to 6:12 per km.\nWeekly running time: approximately 42 minutes.\n\n---\n\n**Week 5**\n\n| Day | Session | Structure | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy run | 5 min walk warm-up, then 17 min continuous easy run | |\n| Thursday | Easy run | 5 min walk warm-up, then 15 min continuous easy run | |\n| Saturday | Easy run | 5 min walk warm-up, then 18 min continuous easy run | |\n\nPace: 5:45 to 6:05 per km.\nWeekly running time: approximately 50 minutes.\n\n---\n\n**Week 6**\n\n| Day | Session | Structure | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy run | 5 min walk warm-up, then 20 min continuous easy run | |\n| Thursday | Easy run | 5 min walk warm-up, then 18 min continuous easy run | |\n| Saturday | Easy run | 5 min walk warm-up, then 20 min continuous easy run | |\n\nPace: 5:40 to 6:05 per km.\nWeekly running time: approximately 58 minutes.\n\n---\n\n### Phase 3: Consolidating and Planning Next Steps (Weeks 7 to 8)\n\nIf you have reached 20 continuous minutes pain-free by Week 6, Weeks 7 and 8 are about demonstrating consistency at that level. This is also the point to return to your physiotherapist to discuss what comes next, whether that is extending duration, adding a fourth day, or beginning to introduce light quality work.\n\n---\n\n**Week 7**\n\n| Day | Session | Structure | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy run | 5 min walk warm-up, then 20 min continuous easy run | |\n| Thursday | Easy run | 5 min walk warm-up, then 20 min continuous easy run | |\n| Saturday | Easy run | 5 min walk warm-up, then 20 min continuous easy run | |\n\nPace: 5:35 to 6:00 per km.\nWeekly running time: approximately 60 minutes.\n\n---\n\n**Week 8 (Deload and Assessment)**\n\n| Day | Session | Structure | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy run | 5 min walk warm-up, then 15 min continuous easy run | |\n| Thursday | Easy run | 5 min walk warm-up, then 15 min continuous easy run | |\n| Saturday | Easy run | 5 min walk warm-up, then 15 min continuous easy run | |\n\nPace: 5:45 to 6:10 per km.\nWeekly running time: approximately 45 minutes.\n\nBook a physiotherapy follow-up before or during this week. Come with data: how many sessions were pain-free, at what point in each run (if any) the foot spoke up, and how you felt the morning after Saturday runs.\n\n---\n\n## Pain Response Protocol\n\nThis applies across all 8 weeks without exception.\n\n| Signal | Action |\n|---|---|\n| Mild foot discomfort during run | Take a 2 to 3 minute walk break. Resume at easy pace if discomfort resolves. |\n| Discomfort that does not resolve with walking | End the session. Log the time and what you were doing. |\n| Pain that persists into the next day | Do not run. Contact your physiotherapist. |\n| Pain-free session | Note it. This is useful data for your next physio visit. |\n\n---\n\n## What Happens After Week 8\n\nThis plan ends at the 20-minute continuous mark. That is a meaningful milestone, but it is a foundation, not a finish line. What comes next depends on what your physiotherapist clears and how the foot has responded.\n\nRealistic trajectories from here, assuming good response:\n\n- Extend long run duration toward 30 to 40 minutes over 4 to 6 more weeks\n- Add a fourth running day\n- Begin reintroducing structured easy strides (not speed work) once cleared\n- Set a return-to-race goal, with 5K being a reasonable first target given your base\n\nYour pre-injury fitness will come back faster than it was originally built. Cardiovascular adaptation returns relatively quickly once load tolerance is re-established. The fascia sets the timeline, not your lungs.\n\n---\n\n## One Practical Note on Footwear and Surface\n\nThis is within coaching scope. Softer surfaces reduce peak plantar load on each footstrike. If you have a choice between road and grass or packed trail for any session, the softer surface is worth the detour right now. Worn-out shoes with compressed midsoles have a similar effect to hard surfaces. If your current shoes have significant mileage on them, it may be worth discussing with your physio whether updated footwear is part of their recommendation.\n\n---\n\nWhere do you want to start? Any part of the structure you want to talk through before Week 1?"
        }
